04024nam a22005895i 9780822393498DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223934987 a10.1515/97808223934982doi  a(DE-B1597)554055  a(OCoLC)746566064  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN6538.N5 7aART0380002bisacsh04a709.041 aJones, Kellie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEyeMinded :bLiving and Writing Contemporary Art /cKellie Jones, Imamu Amiri Baraka. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b27 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Art in the Family -- tPart one. On Diaspora -- tPert two. In Visioning -- tPart three. Making Multiculturalism -- tPart Four. Abstract Truths -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA daughter of the poets Hettie Jones and Amiri Baraka, Kellie Jones grew up immersed in a world of artists, musicians, and writers in Manhattan's East Village and absorbed in black nationalist ideas about art, politics, and social justice across the river in Newark. The activist vision of art and culture that she learned in those two communities, and especially from her family, has shaped her life and work as an art critic and curator. Featuring selections of her writings from the past twenty years, EyeMinded reveals Jones's role in bringing attention to the work of African American, African, Latin American, and women artists who have challenged established art practices. Interviews that she conducted with the painter Howardena Pindell, the installation and performance artist David Hammons, and the Cuban sculptor Kcho appear along with pieces on the photographers Dawoud Bey, Lorna Simpson, and Pat Ward Williams; the sculptor Martin Puryear; the assemblage artist Betye Saar; and the painters Jean-Michel Basquiat, Norman Lewis, and Al Loving. Reflecting Jones's curatorial sensibility, this collection is structured as a dialogue between her writings and works by her parents, her sister Lisa Jones, and her husband Guthrie P. Ramsey Jr. EyeMinded offers a glimpse into the family conversation that has shaped and sustained Jones, insight into the development of her critical and curatorial vision, and a survey of some of the most important figures in contemporary art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAfrican American art. 0aAfrican American artists. 0aArt, Americany20th century. 0aArt, Moderny21st century. 7aART / American / African-American.2bisacsh1 aBaraka, Imamu Amiri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393498zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393498423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393498.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles